SIMPLE: trencher
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trencher
<hw>Trench"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trencheoir</ets>, F. <ets>tranchoir</ets>, fr. <ets>trancher</ets>
to cut, carve. See <er>Trench</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who trenches; esp., one who cuts or digs ditches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large wooden plate or platter, as for table
use.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The table; hence, the pleasures of the table;
food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It could be no ordinary declension of nature that could bring some
men, after an ingenuous education, to place their ⟦ldquo⟧summum
bonum⟦rdquo⟧ upon their <qex>trenchers</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trencher cap</b></col>, <cd>the cap worn by studens at
Oxford and Cambridge Universities, having a stiff, flat, square
appendage at top. A similar cap used in the United States is called
<altname>Oxford cap</altname>, <altname>mortar board</altname>,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Trencher fly</b></col>, <cd>a person who haunts the
tables of others; a parasite.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<au>L'Estrange.</au> -- <col><b>Trencher friend</b></col>, <cd>one who
frequents the tables of others; a sponger.</cd> -- <col><b>Trencher
mate</b></col>, <cd>a table companion; a parasite; a trencher fly.</cd>
<au>Hooker.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trencher-man</ent>⟦br⟧
